Step-by-step reasoning:

1. Key psychological mechanisms:
 • Responder behavior is influenced by the offered monetary split as well as by the discrepancy between the offer and the fairness benchmark implied by the participant’s token allocation.
 • A bonus effect is expected when the offer exceeds the fairness reference and a penalty when it falls short.
 • Diminishing sensitivity is assumed so that larger deviations do not lead to linear changes in utility.

2. Mechanism interaction:
 • Compute a fairness benchmark f from token_self, token_opp, and combined_earning.
 • Calculate the deviation (Δ) between the actual monetary split (split_self) and f.
 • If Δ is positive (offer exceeds fairness), add a bonus that increases with ln(1+Δ) scaled by a positive sensitivity parameter.
 • If Δ is negative (offer falls short of fairness), subtract a penalty that increases with ln(1+|Δ|) scaled by a loss‐aversion parameter.
 • Thus utility is the sum of the monetary offer plus an adjustment based on the logarithmic deviation from fairness.

3. Mathematical formulation:
 • Define f = (token_self/(token_self+token_opp))×combined_earning.
 • Let Δ = split_self − f.
 • Then, the utility is given piecewise by
  if Δ ≥ 0:
   U_accept = split_self + tau_param * ln(1+Δ)
  if Δ < 0:
   U_accept = split_self − lambda_param * ln(1+|Δ|)
 • This model uses two learnable parameters (tau_param and lambda_param) and maps the observed variables directly onto the computed utility.

4. Parameter calibration and mapping:
 • The learnable parameter tau_param calibrates the bonus effect when the offer exceeds the fairness reference.
 • The learnable parameter lambda_param calibrates the penalty effect when the offer falls short.
 • This formulation allows direct computation of utility from split_self, token_self, token_opp, and combined_earning. Higher utility will later be converted to choice probabilities (after adding a temperature parameter externally).

Below is the full model specification, variable descriptions, and a brief summary.

<MODEL>
Let f = (token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) * combined_earning  
Let Δ = split_self - f  
U_accept = I(Δ ≥ 0) · [ split_self + tau_param · ln(1 + Δ) ] + I(Δ < 0) · [ split_self - lambda_param · ln(1 + (f - split_self)) ]
</MODEL>

